Ban on coeducation: Taliban 
Local Talibans of the Gul Bahadur group have distributed a pamphlet in Miran Shah (Capital of Southern Waziristan) and in other Tehsils in which government and semi-government coeducational institutes have been threatened. 
The pamphlet stated that if coeducation institutes are not closed by the 5th of January, action will be taken against them. 
The pamphlet said that women are banned to have ID Cards for government aid and for educational purposes, and women are prohibited to go to NADRA's Offices in all Tehsils. 
The announcement on the ban of women ID Card has been made at a time when almost 200 women have submitted forms in NADRA Offices in Southern Waziristan for Benazir Income Support Program. 
According to local people, the pamphlet issued by Taliban was announced on the loudspeakers of all the Masjids. 
However, it was not mentioned in the letter that separate educational institutipns for women are banned. 
According to the pamphlet, after this announcement, if a woman gets caught when out to get education or get her ID made, she and her family will be punished under law.
Besides this, in the area of Bannu, the police says that a tunnel was blasted by gunpowder on Sunday on Bannu Mir Insha Road, killing one pedestrian and injuring another.
The injured was admitted to Bannu civil hospital.
Target Killing: More dead bodies found.
According to the police, on Sunday morning, two decapitated bodies were found in the areas of the main Mangora, Green square and Sohrab khan square.
The deceased were said to be related to Frontier core and the police.
An eyewitness said that a letter was also found near the bodies in which there was a threat that whoever picks up these bodies before 11 in the morning is responsible for his own death.
Locals say that the bodies were lying in the market until 11:00 A.M., but later security officials picked up both bodies and transferred them to the hospital.
There has been a dangerous rise in the numbers of target killing during the last few weeks in the city of Mangora and surrounding areas.
Local citizens including women and security officials are being killed
According to local sources, more than thirty people have been killed to date in these kinds of incidents.
So far no organization has taken responsibility for these killings.
The spokesman for the local Taliban in Swat, Muslim Khan, stated on Saturday that the dead bodies found on Friday included those of his tribe and also included the dead body of the Taliban commander in Deolai, Rafiullah.
Muslim Khan said that Rafiullah had been in custody of the security forces for the past one and half months.
He had said that the local taliban send notice before killing any one. On the other hand common citizens are worried about these incidents in Mengora.
According to the local people, a large number of security forces are deployed in Mengora but despite this the attacks on the citizens are increasing.
